<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1088,2015]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,411,1196,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Description. Male</emphasis>
. Whole fly as 
<figureCitation box="[570,651,1197,1223]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
. Frons as 
<figureCitation box="[759,840,1197,1223]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
, with microtrichia restricted to edges (
<figureCitation box="[1264,1346,1197,1223]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). Cheek with 4 bristles and jowl with 2 that are longer and more robust. Postpedicels, palps and proboscis as 
<figureCitation box="[1291,1375,1233,1259]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
, with postpedicels lacking SPS vesicles (
<figureCitation box="[542,626,1269,1295]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
). Labella with numerous small bristles on ventral faces (
<figureCitation box="[1254,1338,1269,1295]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
). Notopleuron with 3 bristles, with no cleft in front of these, and mesopleuron with hairs (
<figureCitation box="[1060,1144,1304,1331]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
). Scutellum (
<figureCitation box="[1291,1372,1305,1332]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
) with an anterior pair of hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdomen as 
<figureCitation box="[907,988,1341,1367]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
, with hairs on segments 3–6 of venter 6. Tergites 2 to 4 as 
<figureCitation box="[350,433,1377,1403]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[630,758,1376,1403]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–54" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1346,1371]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1317]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,181,1320]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 49–54. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 49, hypopygium left face; 50, epandrium left face; 51, hypopygium right face; 52, front tarsus; 53, hind femur; 54, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573376/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs 49–51</figureCitation>
. Legs yellowish brown with a darker tip to hind femur. Fore tarsus with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and 5 a little longer than 4 (
<figureCitation box="[1082,1165,1412,1439]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–54" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1346,1371]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1317]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,181,1320]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 49–54. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 49, hypopygium left face; 50, epandrium left face; 51, hypopygium right face; 52, front tarsus; 53, hind femur; 54, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573376/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 52</figureCitation>
). Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.9 times its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur longer than those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation box="[366,452,1484,1511]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–54" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1346,1371]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1317]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,181,1320]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 49–54. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 49, hypopygium left face; 50, epandrium left face; 51, hypopygium right face; 52, front tarsus; 53, hind femur; 54, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573376/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
), being 
<quantity box="[547,650,1485,1511]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="0.08">0.08 mm</quantity>
long. Hind tibia with 14–15 moderately differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[971,1052,1520,1547]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–54" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1346,1371]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1317]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,181,1320]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 49–54. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 49, hypopygium left face; 50, epandrium left face; 51, hypopygium right face; 52, front tarsus; 53, hind femur; 54, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573376/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 54</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[1066,1228,1520,1547]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.725" metricValueMax="1.75" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="1.725" valueMax="1.75" valueMin="1.7">1.70–1.75 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.43–0.44. Costal ratios 3.7–3.8: 2.20: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[916,1015,1557,1583]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="0.13">0.13 mm</quantity>
long. Hair at base of vein 3 only 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="0.03">0.03 mm</quantity>
long. With 4 axillary bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity box="[765,865,1593,1619]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="0.13">0.13 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere knob pale.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1088,2015]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1628,1655]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key to the males of British species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[838,984,1629,1655]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref21228" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to triplet 104; but this is in part revised by 
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L. &amp; Haggqvist, S." box="[272,583,1665,1691]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref21481" refString="Disney, R. H. L. &amp; Haggqvist, S. (2018) Morphological recognition of the species of the Megaselia lucifrons (Schmitz) group (Diptera: Phoridae). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 154, 1 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.31184 / M 00138908.1541.3911" type="journal article" year="2018">Disney &amp; Häggqvist (2018)</bibRefCitation>
, in which it runs to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lundbeck)" authorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[800,1081,1665,1692]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subnitida">
<emphasis box="[800,940,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. subnitida</emphasis>
(Lundbeck)
</taxonomicName>
. However, it differs in a number of details considered below. For the rest of the world the Nearctic species 
<taxonomicName authority="Borgmeier (1964)" authorityName="Borgmeier" authorityYear="1964" box="[1004,1342,1701,1728]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cribella">
<emphasis box="[1004,1130,1701,1727]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. cribella</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Borgmeier, T." box="[1139,1342,1701,1728]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="257 - 416" refId="ref20921" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1964) Revision of the North American Phorid flies. Part II. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Aphiochaeta (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, Petropolis, 7, 257 - 416." type="journal article" year="1964">Borgmeier (1964)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is similar, but its longer costal index, position of the anterolateral frontal bristles and the tapered hypandrial lobe of the hypopygium exclude this species. With regard to the differences of our species from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[1121,1264,1773,1799]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subnitida">
<emphasis box="[1121,1264,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. subnitida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends 0.76–0.90 times its length contrasting with 0.61–0.62 times in 
<emphasis box="[1177,1325,1809,1835]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[1177,1322,1809,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subnitida">M. subnitida</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The hairs below the basal half of the hind femur are longer (
<figureCitation box="[709,790,1844,1871]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–54" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1346,1371]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1317]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,181,1320]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 49–54. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 49, hypopygium left face; 50, epandrium left face; 51, hypopygium right face; 52, front tarsus; 53, hind femur; 54, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573376/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
) than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[888,1029,1845,1871]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subnitida">
<emphasis box="[888,1029,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. subnitida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1044,1125,1844,1871]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–56" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1807,1832]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1428,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,1428,1781]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 55–56. Megaselia subnitida male. 55, abdominal tergites 1 to 4; 56, hind femur. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573378/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 56</figureCitation>
) and the longer hairs on the lateral fifths of abdominal tergite 2 are more numerous and extend almost to the lateral margins (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1315,1881,1907]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–48" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[183,1403,181,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 39–48. Megaselia kaleybarensis n. sp. male. 39, whole fly; 40, frons; 41, part of frons enlarged; 42, postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 43, postpedicel; 44, ventral face of proboscis; 45, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 46, scutellum; 47, abdomen; 48, tergites 1 to 4. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573374/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
), but in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subnitida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">M. subnitida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are fewer and end well before the lateral edges and the posterolateral hairs are longer (
<figureCitation box="[1289,1373,1916,1943]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–56" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1807,1832]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1428,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1435,1428,1781]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 55–56. Megaselia subnitida male. 55, abdominal tergites 1 to 4; 56, hind femur. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573378" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573378/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
). The hypopygia seem very similar.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,717,1989,2015]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1088,2015]" box="[199,717,1989,2015]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1989,2015]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after the Kaleybar region.
</paragraph>
